commit_message:
Don't register options in __init__

Each driver currently registers its own config options in the
constructor. This is not a good thing and has caused things like
`dynamic_conf` to happen.

This patch adds a method that is called in the constructor of the base
class that goes through the driver's options and registers them. The
method catches duplicated exceptions. We don't care about those for now
and we assume the driver consumer knows what it's doing.

Bug: #1372335
Change-Id: I3341416332a0e620e428308f463d1bb635927a5d

The initializer for the python-troveclient HTTPClient class
fails if passed a None for an auth_url.
This patch modifies the inializer to not call rstrip

commit_message:
trove client HTTPClient __init__ fails if auth_url None

The initializer for the python-troveclient HTTPClient class
fails if passed a None for an auth_url.
This patch modifies the inializer to not call rstrip
if auth_url is None, matching the initalizers in
python-novaclient and python-neutronclient

Change-Id: I01fdf2dffe3c149edeaef66db6d047e462f985d9
Closes-bug: #1375982

commit_message:
Use different timeouts for create and restore

Restoring an instance from a backup can take significantly longer than
just creating an instance. Introduce a new timeout for the restore case
with a higher default value

Change-Id: I44af03e9b2c966dd94fcfd0ff475f112ac21be5b
Closes-Bug: 1356645

commit_message:
Workaround for 'File exists' test failure

Adds code to create the assets directory that django_pyscss
intends to create for scss.  This avoids throwing an exception
in concurrency scenarios

Change-Id: Ic55e2a7ce59ec9b7550a7412697cb8d6563d98a3
Closes-bug: #1367590

The original thought - to use the build to separately upload
config.json for our CORS draft build - didn't work because
of lack of path munging control. Instead we've declared a
separate build target called 'build:draft' that compiles an
appropriate client, which can then be uploaded in one go.

Change-Id: I16ad8fd8b90aca93929e68ef3033715e0666795b
"}]
commit_message:
Call build:draft instead of build for js-draft build

The original thought - to use the build to separately upload
config.json for our CORS draft build - didn't work because
of lack of path munging control. Instead we've declared a
separate build target called 'build:draft' that compiles an
appropriate client, which can then be uploaded in one go.

Change-Id: I16ad8fd8b90aca93929e68ef3033715e0666795b

commit_message:
V1.1: Add id property to messages in claims

The id property should be also added to messages returned from the
claims endpoints: claim messages and get claim.

Change-Id: Ida02aa4e1c794adb3ae7ea26cdd250ae45cac5bd
Partially-implements: blueprint api-v1.1-response-document-changes

commit_message:
Make the replication snapshot timeout configurable

There is no way to tell how long the snapshot for replication
will take, and we have no good way to poll for the slave state.
Eventually, we will need to have an intelligent poll (perhaps
based on guest heartbeats), but in the meantime we will have
the the snapshot use a configurable timeout which can be set
as needed, and independently of the agent_call timeouts.

Co-Authored-By: Nikhil Manchanda <SlickNik@gmail.com>
Change-Id: I6316d748e91d1ec3eebe25a14bb43fbfe10db669
Closes-bug: 1362310

commit_message:
Do not run fwaas API tests in smoke

Now that we are running full tempest against neutron, and because fwaas
is not part of core functionality (and not fully baked). Remove these
test from smoke as part of the effort to only test advanced services
against neutron and not against all projects.

Related patch: Ib315d30ff3c4463203f7ebe00e159a9680cf1616

Change-Id: I2e0ce9641becabbeed5f6ad82ad478d84a37f36f

commit_message:
Add python-keystoneclient-federation to the Identity program

Similar to the python-keystoneclient-kerberos auth plugin, the federation
auth plugin for keystoneclient requires external dependencies that should
not be required for all installations of keystoneclient. Therefore this
plugin has been added as a separate repository and package (on pypi).

Change-Id: I8e6ba4d8ef41dce84748574956fba485ec79919b

http://status.openstack.org/zuul/'}, {'account_id': 7253, 'date': '2014-03-24 21:25:34.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

Hi Thomas,

I'd like to re-open that discussion, since it's very useful to have a template-level image name-to-image ID mapping.

This feature would allow a template author to pin their templates to known-good image IDs, while retaining the user-friendliness of passing image names as parameters.  This is necessary because the global image name-to-image ID mappings in Glance can change frequently and introduce subtle differences that can cause configuration scripts to fail.  In the end, this reduces the maintainability of templates.

In light of this use-case, I don't think whether or not HOT looks like a clone of CFN is a valid consideration."}, {'account_id': 7256, 'date': '2014-03-24 21:35:48.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

IIRC that original discussion was around the general kludgy nature of Fn::FindInMap and it didn't feel very "declarative". Discussion was around the need for it and we've recently seen real issues with mapping image names to proper ID's in our public cloud because of shifting names or differences in data centers. While I don't personally *like* the map approach, it does seem like a valid use case on the surface. I wonder if we don't need a better way to solve this particular use case via being able to specify image meta as a requirement and having the validation/lookups in nova_utils be able to resolve a best match?'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-03-24 22:19:22.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Works for me

'}, {'account_id': 7193, 'date': '2014-03-25 12:45:36.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

Hi Jason,

I understand the use case of proving a map of validated image IDs, but I do not (yet) buy the need for putting this into the template. In my mind, a template is something that should be portable across environments. If user a develops a template on his OpenStack, I want to take it and run it on my OpenStack. And there the image IDs will most probably be different. So IMO this could rather be something that belongs into an environment file than in the template.
Would that be something that can help address your use case?

> In light of this use-case, I don't think whether or not HOT looks like a clone of CFN is a valid consideration.

I agree, that just this use case and just the addition of "mapping" makes HOT a clone of CFN. But if we add more and more CFNinsh things I see the risk of this happening. If we need something additional in HOT, maybe we should crisply define what it is and give a different name? Just to avoid that people thing "oh, this is this multi-dimensional map thing that exists in CFN". ... just a thought.'}, {'account_id': 7193, 'date': '2014-03-25 12:51:12.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

Hi Randall,

to your point:

> I wonder if we don't need a better way to solve this particular use case via being able to specify image meta as a requirement and having the validation/lookups in nova_utils be able to resolve a best match?

Yes, I think this is exactly what we should shoot for. I.e. instead of taking a short step and using the mappings that most people did not like when we started HOT, let's see what the right solution would be. E.g. by using a more metadata-based lookup of images.

We actually have a similar use case related to flavors: today everything is based on flavor names, but there is no guarantee that "m1.big" means the same in all environments (only as long as everyone keeps the defaults, this is true). Sometimes, app deployers really want to be able to specific exact requirements on cpu, memory, disk and in such cases it might make sense to lookup the right flavor to use based on this metadata.'}, {'account_id': 7253, 'date': '2014-03-26 15:21:28.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

Hi Thomas,

A template author needs to have the option of making the image name-to-image ID mapping tightly-coupled to a particular template.  The obvious way to do that would be to put the mapping in the template itself.  I'm open to other suggestions, but an environment file wouldn't satisfy this requirement."}, {'account_id': 7193, 'date': '2014-03-26 15:34:42.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

Hi Jason,

I got the general requirement on the one hand, but still believe this should not be tightly bound to the template, since image IDs will vary across different OpenStack instances. So the template would be bound to one instance. Therefore, I thought this would rather belong to the environment. Sounds like we would need a way for binding an environment definition to a template then in one OpenStack deployment.

Anyway, I don't want completely hold things off. Would be good to get some more opinions on that topic."}, {'account_id': 4328, 'date': '2014-03-26 16:19:14.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

IMO any mappings belong in the environment.  Decoupling the declarative model from changes in the environment is exactly what the environment was designed to do, so personally I see this as a step in the wrong direction."}, {'account_id': 7253, 'date': '2014-03-26 17:07:31.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Abandoned

Thanks for the comments.'}, {'account_id': 4257, 'date': '2014-03-26 19:18:52.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: (1 inline comment)

I can see both sides of this argument.

On the one hand, I've long been an advocate of giving users the tools to allow them to e.g. replicate a previously launched stack completely, and having stuff stored outside of version control is not helpful on that front.

On the other hand, templates are supposed to be portable between clouds, and the environment is for customising to a particular cloud.

On balance, I am inclined to agree with Thomas and Steve. This could perhaps be better solved by giving better names to your Glance images (and maybe we should document this), although I agree that it's unsatisfying to leave it up to the user's policies."}, {'account_id': 7253, 'date': '2014-08-19 21:32:19.000000000', 'content': 'Restored

section in the environment.

commit_message:
Ensure tempest writes a full manifest

The tempest element uses pip install after generating the manifest,
meaning that it installs software not listed in its manifest.

Fix it so that it writes the manifest after the last of these
installs.

Change-Id: I456d650c0bcba448cb18efad95e7daeccd5d9e0b

commit_message:
Don't use keystone client before initializing it

Eventlet was calling poll() before the KeystoneDriver finished, so the the
keystone client object was not initialized yet.  This caused an AttributeError
in KeystoneDriver.  This change separates the KeystoneDriver constructor from
initialization of the keystone client object.  This separation ensures that
the first time eventlet calls update_from_datasource(), the KeystoneDriver is
fully initialized.

Change-Id: I55f76d5dc115920ea04d0a954919d9ef329fb886

commit_message:
Add DEPLOYMENT_MODE to local_settings.py

DEPLOYMENT_MODE determine if we do flavor matching, it can be "poc" (No) or "scale" (Yes).
This is used in Tuskar-ui to show flavor administration options etc.

Change-Id: I6a1b1cbb9cfe8d2750023d6ea633cf3390468c43

[{'created': '2014-09-09 22:00:07.000000000', 'message': 'Recommendation to Adopt DCO as CLA

At its July 2014 meeting, the OpenStack Foundation Board of Directors
heard information about the impact and options to address the
OpenStack Contributor License Agreement.  One of the questions raised
was whether the issues being brought forward were simply the opinion
of one member of the Board.

This resolution clarifies that the TC believes that the current CLA is
problematic and the DCO should be considered instead.

Change-Id: I5da90bd9ae3c7c08c028aa8dd3d0521b8b44d593

This resolution clarifies that the TC believes that the current CLA is
problematic and the DCO should be considered instead.

Change-Id: I5da90bd9ae3c7c08c028aa8dd3d0521b8b44d593
'}]
commit_message:
Recommendation to Adopt DCO as CLA

At its July 2014 meeting, the OpenStack Foundation Board of Directors
heard information about the impact and options to address the
OpenStack Contributor License Agreement.  One of the questions raised
was whether the issues being brought forward were simply the opinion
of one member of the Board.

This resolution clarifies that the TC believes that the current CLA is
problematic and the DCO should be considered instead.

Change-Id: I5da90bd9ae3c7c08c028aa8dd3d0521b8b44d593

commit_message:
Detect if a node is being reused

Drop a file into the logs directory containing job details, if we find
it already existed this means the node has already been used.

Change-Id: If8151756c8273b57bdbda8e02917210081a8f97c
Related-Bug: #1370275

commit_message:
Switch to new setup-neutron

Switch to the new setup-neutron provided by os-cloud-config, and to
ease developer (and git) confusion, remove and ignore the old
setup-neutron script.

Genuine question: How does this element relate to TripleO?'}, {'account_id': 11094, 'date': '2014-08-21 20:20:23.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

This element installs the monasca-agent which is used for monitoring the system it is on. It doesn't directly relate to TripleO. I thought the repo included elements that are used when building systems with TripleO. For example snmpd is in this repo and is similar in that it installs tools for monitoring a system."}, {'account_id': 12512, 'date': '2014-08-21 20:42:29.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

This is the agent and is installed on all machines you want to monitor. It is independent from the server stack and can stand alone. Given that I think it makes sense for it to be submitted individually.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-08-21 20:51:46.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

My feeling is that if this is unrelated to TripleO then it shouldn't be in the tripleo-image-elements repo

The snmpd element is used by TripleO since 5f19d72d (it's deployed onto the overcloud as part of an undercloud ceilometer deployment), so I don't think that can be used to justify adding in arbitrary unrelated element.

On the other hand - the snmpd element seems to have been sitting in the repo for a year before that change started using it - so maybe that actually *is* a good justification for adding in this element."}, {'account_id': 11094, 'date': '2014-09-30 19:35:47.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned'}]

commit_message:
Add more checks for zuul/layout.yaml

Check that each project (with exception of z/tempest) has a merge-check
template.
Check projects - so far stackforge only - for alphabetical order.

The merge template check is taken from a test that Jeremy shared.

Change-Id: I2bc457ddfe0eca787bb88ceeb919f89d491978d7
Co-Authored-By: Jeremy Stanley <fungi@yuggoth.org>

Use alarmDefintionId instead of alarmId to find the right notificaion.
Further changes are needed to complete this change.

commit_message:
Fix resource cleanup in server rescue tests

If server rescue tests are skipped then the resource cleanup method
terminates with AttributeError: type object has no attribute 'volume'.
The fix checks whether volume exist before operating with it.

Change-Id: I6ae7f7bb2ba73313db676bafd597c0934704959a

commit_message:
javelin: Detach the volume before destruction

In Icehouse, a volume needs to be detached before it can be deleted.

Closes-Bug:  #1375476

Change-Id: Ic1c8e79fc1efa46ac9a70e288166cd5e0d823cfa

non-stackforge projects out of the section.

commit_message:
Use tox -e zuul for layout test

Adjust tox environment, the check_projects_yaml_alphabetized.sh script
only works with gerrit/projects.yaml but not with layout.yaml, so remove
the call.

Change the job to use tox -e zuul.

Change-Id: I70d918ec1de94c6ec9aa0c2c6647aa8c791df303

[{'created': '2014-09-02 20:09:17.000000000', 'message': "Add a new non-blocking delete option for images

Currently images can be deleted immediately with a blocking call or marked as
'pending_delete' and deleted in the future by a scrubber. This patch adds a
third configurable option to delete images immediately in the background.

Change-Id: I043c6743ef34cd4e70657c73f7bded0ae51ba335
Closes-Bug: 1316234
"}]
commit_message:
Add a new non-blocking delete option for images

Currently images can be deleted immediately with a blocking call or marked as
'pending_delete' and deleted in the future by a scrubber. This patch adds a
third configurable option to delete images immediately in the background.

Change-Id: I043c6743ef34cd4e70657c73f7bded0ae51ba335
Closes-Bug: 1316234

commit_message:
Adds to KMIP secret store test coverage

Adds a few small changes to make the KMIP Secret Store plugin more
robust, along with unit tests that raise the kmip_secret_store test
coverage to 100% (once pykmip is added test-requirements.txt)

Change-Id: Id3772e05e269a8d96c7205ade49d429e5fc0b50f

commit_message:
Tune up mod_wsgi settings in example configuration

Explicitly set mod-wsgi process-group to ceilometer-api in sample
This gives the process a good name in process listings.

Set number of process and threads to two and ten respectively. This
represents a reasonable setting to achieve moderate levels of
concurrency.

Change-Id: Iada6126cb525d597cc385c2d63e6228ef08d55a7

commit_message:
Use oslo.msg retry API in rpc publisher

This patch removes the ceilometer hack around rabbitmq configuration
to use the oslo.messaging API to retry rpc connection.

Closes bug #1244698
Co-Authored-By: Ala Rezmerita <ala.rezmerita@cloudwatt.com>

Change-Id: I162f2ce7ba7f6644d995dfeef8b0ef5e2727c226

But I agree there is a problem that needs solving here.

It feels like kicking the scrubber directly, rather than waiting for it, and making billing stop billing when you enter pending_delete, feels like a better option?

That way you get a consistent API experience (I think we should deprecated the synchronous API config), and you simply configure the behaviour of the scrubber, which is free to schedule a delete whenever the deployer feels that is best, because billing will stop billing the user when it goes into pending_delete.'}, {'account_id': 11356, 'date': '2014-09-23 17:31:19.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

commit_message:
macros: Manage metadata.json file in puppet-lint jobs

Since puppet 3.x, Puppet Labs Forge accept only the metadata.json file
for module description (Modulefile is now deprecated). Our puppet-lint
jobs use the Modulefile to determine module name; this patch keep the «
retro-compat. » with Modulefile, but fetch the module name in
metadata.json file if available.

Change-Id: I1738ee14706d136837b2c8fe4ffa741907291bb8

commit_message:
Move python33 test for Keystone to experimental

py33 tests are not functional at the moment for Keystone, instead
of strictly non-voting, move it to experimental so it can be triggered
when someone is working on py33 compatibility, not on every check.

Change-Id: Ie9a8ed131f3c0338dead7e3a5c8da0fcc89add58

[{'created': '2014-09-26 13:51:49.000000000', 'message': 'Stop using deprecated TESTR_FULL option

The TESTR_FULL option was added back when tempest was running by
default with nosestests serially to test using testr in parallel.
However, this migration happened >1yr ago and the testr-full job is
just a duplicate of the regular full now. This commit removes all uses
of it from job definitions.

Change-Id: I8af1b4bc0623e89786b34359c6e75aacb21b91ab
'}]
commit_message:
Stop using deprecated TESTR_FULL option

The TESTR_FULL option was added back when tempest was running by
default with nosestests serially to test using testr in parallel.
However, this migration happened >1yr ago and the testr-full job is
just a duplicate of the regular full now. This commit removes all uses
of it from job definitions.

Change-Id: I8af1b4bc0623e89786b34359c6e75aacb21b91ab

commit_message:
Fix indentation in rally-designate job config

Builder's parameters should not be on the same level as builder.
Otherwise bash script will be generated with errors.

Change-Id: I5816f41f54d5506f0cbe72ffbd1271d2834d0864

commit_message:
Change keystone class to inherit keystone::params

The keystone class should inherit keystone::params, so default
parameter values are available.

Change-Id: I7d5ca882c52567687df96ef1114cbb6cf8e8b2bf
Closes-Bug: 1375465

commit_message:
Use ConfigFilter for opts

This will prevent them being registered on the global config object
and becoming available to consuming applications.

Change-Id: Ibddb876d18c6aefef9dca08cf5883d8bdca17925

commit_message:
Make lockutils main() a console entry point

This is more lib-ish than calling python -m on the module.

As part of this change, I also improved the unit tests for this code.
Before we weren't unsetting OSLO_LOCK_PATH before calling the main
function, so we had no way of knowing if it was being set correctly.

I also added a test case to verify return value propagation and
removed a private method that was never called.

Change-Id: I6c35b5409bf567767c5c71b9041dd7f7a012255d

commit_message:
Expose lockutils opts to config generator

* Adds an opts module for the config generator to use.
* Makes the opts in lockutils private since we don't want consumers
  using them directly.
* Moves the options to an oslo_concurrency group with appropriate
  deprecated_group settings to keep existing configs working.

Change-Id: Ifdb4d99e27588e8a91d941c60b248ea526c06e0a

(1 comment)

Vincent, thanks for making add_vdisk_qos(), update_vdisk_qos() consistent.  I have one question about the how unsupported QoS parameter is handled.  If backend raises exception in that case, then this patch changes the behavior to sliently ignore them in driver, that worth documenting(e.g. commit message should mention behavior change and add DocImpact).  If backend simply ignores unsupported QoS like this patch is doing in driver, I'm more than happy to +2/A your change.  Thanks!"}, {'account_id': 2861, 'date': '2014-09-26 09:31:08.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 10:

Zhiteng, thank you for your comments. From the cinder perspective, users can specify any parameters for QoS, but only supported QoS keys ware picked up by the backend storage drivers, like solidfire, hp, storwize, etc. The QoS code follows the similar patterns, all the driver supported keys are saved in a dict, which is used to match if the user specifies supported parameter. The behaviour for unsupported qos parameters is they will be ignored.

From the storwize driver's perspective, after the user specified QoS keys pass into the driver, the QoS will be filtered first with the method get_vdisk_param before reaching the code line, where you give your comment. I check the parameters here in add_vdisk_qos is just to make sure that the code is 100% safe to execute. In this case, unsupported keys are neglected.

I guess it is good to describe all the available parameters supported by different drivers and state that unsupported parameters will be ignored. I will help the doc with that if it is acceptable for our cinder. What do you think?"}, {'account_id': 2861, 'date': '2014-09-26 09:55:42.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 11.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-09-26 12:15:30.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 11: Verified-1

commit_message:
IBM Storwize driver: Retype the volume with correct empty QoS

* Currently for Storwzie driver, if the new type does not have QoS
configurations, the old QoS configurations remain in the volume after
retyping it. It should be retyped into a volume with empty QoS for the
Storwize driver.
* Refactor three dicts into one for better maintainance of the QoS keys
for Storwize driver.

DocImpact

Change-Id: I2b2801a4ef72ef02c11392ed00b56f5263a8a7e4
Closes-Bug: #1368595

commit_message:
Migrate scenario utils to tempest client

All scenario tests have been migrated to tempest client.
Migrate scenario utils as well, so that we may drop
the OfficialClientManager completely.

Change-Id: I3ec80de961ba289734f9bc811e4789e7d1b5903c
Partially-implements: bp/tempest-client-scenarios

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-09-26 05:32:04.000000000', 'message': 'Add sudo before running tox tests for osc functional

Currently, when running this test, it automatically fails because
the user running tox does not have sufficient permission to run
the tests. Adding a sudo before hand should resolve this issue.

Change-Id: I8543db1c2ecbb6f78eb831ebc9ea1a03625e3542
'}, {'created': '2014-09-26 15:32:26.000000000', 'message': 'Run a shell script instead of tox for osc functional

Currently, when running functional tests for OSC, we try to run
a tox job. It automatically fails because the user running tox does
not have sufficient permission to run the tests.

Suggest just running a single script file that OSC maintains, rather
than having to change infra resources every time something changes.

Change-Id: I8543db1c2ecbb6f78eb831ebc9ea1a03625e3542

commit_message:
Run a shell script instead of tox for osc functional

Currently, when running functional tests for OSC, we try to run
a tox job. It automatically fails because the user running tox does
not have sufficient permission to run the tests.

Suggest just running a single script file that OSC maintains, rather
than having to change infra resources every time something changes.

Change to add functional tests for OSC is here:
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/122605/

Change-Id: I8543db1c2ecbb6f78eb831ebc9ea1a03625e3542

commit_message:
Enable retry tests on comment

One CI feature that Solum should provide is to
allow a user retry tests by commenting with
a particular phrase on the repo, just like
'recheck no bug' for OpenStack. This patch
enables this feature.

Change-Id: If1664410c485fad1289ede3511372ce65d9333f2

commit_message:
Fixes logging in image_import's main module

Some of the logs were not translated. This patch fixes those and
some other logs.

Change-Id: I153b3aef13bdc4a3c0ef477d3bccd93c5c1887ff

OK, that wasn't a helpful suggestion. Here's one that may be more useful:

If we call function.dependencies() on the data then we can see if it references a resource (independently of the template format). In the case where we haven't created the stack yet, we know that there will be no data available in these cases, so we should not attempt to verify constraints. commit_message:
Skip validation if depends on not created resource

Using references on resources defined in template may be cause
of error during validation. This fix checks reference on another
resource and skips validation if resource is in INIT state.

Change-Id: I95531a1603de1e8c4b9f0f4b05b62eebc48beb3c
Co-Authored-By: Zane Bitter <zbitter@redhat.com>
Closes-Bug: #1347571
Closes-Bug: #1339942

commit_message:
Fix subnet residue when resource deletion

Should set resource_id immediately after creating subnet
successful, otherwise the subnet resource will residue
when deletion.

Change-Id: I7974272d6a4b394775d971e2636bd1d4d5b78562
Closes-bug: #1370973

This is setting config file values; why can't this be done in local.conf settings?

I would certainly support adding documentation about it, but it doesn't seem to need its own global variables"}, {'account_id': 6685, 'date': '2014-09-25 19:56:59.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

I tried to use local.conf, and it didn't work for two reasons:
 -- it doesn't preserve the double quotes in the string. For example, the expected nova configuration should be:
     pci_alias = {"name":"cisco","vendor_id":"8086","product_id":"10ed"}
But this is what I got:
     pci_aias = {name:cisco,vendor_id:8086,product_id:10ed}

This caused nova to bail out.

 -- lib/config uses iniset to make changes in the config file. This doesn't work for multi-line config items, which is needed for our case. One way to fix it is to use iniadd, which is slower than iniset. 

Let me open a bug for the above issues.'}, {'account_id': 6698, 'date': '2014-09-30 16:50:15.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: -Code-Review

Based on Ians comments, this is not needed.'}, {'account_id': 6685, 'date': '2014-09-30 17:06:11.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned

Refer to https://bugs.launchpad.net/devstack/+bug/1374118
on how to support the configuration of pci_passthrough_whitelist and pci_alias in local.conf.'}]

This patch adds configuration of pci_passthrough_whitelist and
pci_alias in the nova configuration file. Define either of them as a
shell array. Parenthesis can be omitted if a single item is contained
in the array. Each item in the array is a Json docstring that defines
a dictionary, and therefore needs to be quoted.

Use the variable PCI_WHITELIST to define pci passthrough whitelists.
Supported keys for each item are "vendor_id", "product_id", "address"
or "devname", "physical_network". The keys and the values must be
quoted.

Use the variable PCI_ALIAS to define pci aliases. Supported keys are
"vendor_id", "product_id" and "physical_network". The keys and the
values must be quoted.

Examples:

PCI_WHITELIST=('{"vendor_id":"1137","product_id":"0071","address":"*:0a:00.*","physical_network":"physnet1"}'
               '{"vendor_id":"1137","product_id":"0071"}')

PCI_ALIAS='{"name":"cisco","vendor_id":"8086","product_id":"10ed"}'

Change-Id: I0d2fc2b7c6010fd6ce3d4ec837828091bfafbb18
Closes-Bug: #1373127

commit_message:
Configure pci_passthrough_whitelist and pci_alias

This patch adds configuration of pci_passthrough_whitelist and
pci_alias in the nova configuration file. Define either of them as a
shell array. Parenthesis can be omitted if a single item is contained
in the array. Each item in the array is a Json docstring that defines
a dictionary, and therefore needs to be quoted.

Use the variable PCI_WHITELIST to define pci passthrough whitelists.
Supported keys for each item are "vendor_id", "product_id", "address"
or "devname", "physical_network".

Use the variable PCI_ALIAS to define pci aliases. Supported keys are
"vendor_id", "product_id" and "physical_network".

The keys and the values must be quoted. Use ',' in between the key
value paires, and no space should be used.

Examples:

PCI_WHITELIST=('{"vendor_id":"1137","product_id":"0071","address":"*:0a:00.*","physical_network":"physnet1"}'
               '{"vendor_id":"1137","product_id":"0071"}')

PCI_ALIAS='{"name":"cisco","vendor_id":"8086","product_id":"10ed"}'

Change-Id: I0d2fc2b7c6010fd6ce3d4ec837828091bfafbb18
Closes-Bug: #1373127

commit_message:
Ensure that keystone uses global debug setting

When setting ENABLE_DEBUG_LOG_LEVEL the keystone screen would ignore
this setting and always use the debug mode.

Change-Id: I934443c2976e936198fc93da4cca717e6cb84e6f

commit_message:
Use OpenStack Incubated branding for docs

Barbican is not integrated but incubated. The branding of the web pages at
http://docs.openstack.org/developer/barbican/ should thus be the incubated
branding.

Change-Id: I78a0c988993d9d2947769ee412cb962cb6c4ccde

commit_message:
Allowing all content-types for secret delete

Fixing issue where a secret delete fails if the Accept header
is set to application/json.

Change-Id: Ia60ec76805e7a820578f202ffa06c31579a084db
Closes-Bug: #1326481

commit_message:
Adding size limits for create secret json fields

Setting maxLength for name, algorithm, mode, expiration,
payload_content_type, and payload_content_encoding fields.

Payload size is already validated through other means.

Change-Id: Id48c5ca9e7af6e8a49591787a58427255eee10b7
Closes-Bug: #1335327

commit_message:
Refactor secret functional tests using models and behaviors

Updated the functional tests to use models and behaviors for secrets.
* Adding simple HATEOS-compatible rest client
* Fixing model de/serialization
* Modifying all tests to conform to the new client
* Adding option to load tempest config from local etc
* Incorporating review feedback

Change-Id: I497b4f7bf10a9f47ca399b569d964762505466c9

default list that do not exist. Add the jjb environment to the list.

Add the missing argument to check_projects_yaml_alphabetized.sh and

'}]
commit_message:
Fix up tests after repo reorganization

Fix the default tox configuration so it works properly if a developer
just runs "tox" on their local system by removing environments from the
default list that do not exist. Add the jjb environment to the list.

Add the missing argument to check_projects_yaml_alphabetized.sh and
remove the unused arguments from run-layout.sh.

Exclude the .test directory created by the zuul test environment from
the files checked by flake8.

Change-Id: I72cb9aa3908d16f9e5b6d6445b07819563ce9104

commit_message:
Do not run unit test jobs for oslo-specs

Some of the specs repositories use the unit test job to validate the
contents of the spec file. We do not do that in oslo-specs, so there is
no point in running the job.

Change-Id: I5c2f16097cca5afdd03ba5cac85aa5d5489fd42b

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-07-22 13:23:48.000000000', 'message': 'Enable Nova to log to Logstash

By setting log_config=/etc/nova/logging.conf , providing that file and
creating /var/log/nova to hold disk logs.

A human-readable log will be created as nova.log and a JSON-formatted
log will be created as json.log.

Logs are rotated to use at most 20GB, with 18GB allocated to the
human-readable log.

Change-Id: If925856f83e034fc075c4e3d576fbd6739a478c9
'}, {'created': '2014-07-22 14:53:02.000000000', 'message': 'Prepare Nova to log to Logstash

This patch provides a logrotate configuration and a logging.conf for
Nova. To actually enable the latter, the following passthrough snippet
must be provided:

  {
    "nova": {
      "config": [{
        "section": "DEFAULT",
        "values": [{
             "option": "log_config_append",
             "value": "/etc/nova/logging.conf"
        }]
      }]
    }
  }

A human-readable log will be created as nova.log and a JSON-formatted
log will be created as json.log.

Logs are rotated to use at most 20GB, with 18GB allocated to the
human-readable log.

Change-Id: If925856f83e034fc075c4e3d576fbd6739a478c9

commit_message:
Add beaver element

This installs beaver. Configuration may be supplied via passthrough.

Advances blueprint logstash.

Change-Id: I9293103dc2720bfdf62be3a37273cb776ff8cb31

Hi Ben, thanks for your review. Yes you need to arrange for a thirdparty repo to be available, this can be done using the apt-sources and dpkg elements on Debian. If someone wants to use this on Fedora they'll need to arrange for similar support.

If you check PS1, I included instructions on how to do this in the README.md, but I was asked to remove them."}, {'account_id': 11655, 'date': '2014-08-18 12:38:16.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 9: Code-Review-1

Sorry for the confusion about removing the documentation lines. IMO, even with those lines in the README this is not mergeable - we should find a way for this element to install without expecting operators to perform configuration for some separate element.

Some half-baked ideas on how to solve this:
* add the repos in this element
* grab the packages and install it with wget
* make a more general way to add repositories and run that here
* something else I havent thought of?'}, {'account_id': 10035, 'date': '2014-08-18 17:47:55.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 9:

There is another point that I wont block this patch on but I think needs to be discussed: I assume the purpose of this element is to eventually add logstash, should we be installing that (and therefore this element) by default? This would be very nice for CI reasons...'}, {'account_id': 8688, 'date': '2014-08-19 08:48:09.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 9:

Thanks for your review and suggestions Greg. I have specific requirements to a) not rely on the internet, b) to be able to install from a user-configured repo.

I recognise TripleO has no such problem but it'd be easy to add the dpkg + apt-sources to tripleo-incubator. It feels really wrong to not use the explicit support which has been provided to handle this scenario. Admittedly this hasn't been done for Fedora yet but that's just an oversight imo.

I could include a flag which, if unset, causes this element to add the packages.elasticsearch.org repo? It's a hideous conflation of responsibilities imo but clearly this patch is not going anywhere as is :("}, {'account_id': 10035, 'date': '2014-08-19 19:12:48.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 9:

Any reason to not just download the deb / rpm and dpkg -i to install it? This seems like it would both work by default and allow you to easily override the installed package using DIB_REPOLOCATION_elasticsearch if you download it via source-repositories.'}, {'account_id': 8688, 'date': '2014-09-05 15:34:01.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 10.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-09-05 15:34:04.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 10: Verified+1

commit_message:
Add elasticsearch element

This simply installs elasticsearch. A future patch can add the ability
to customise the configuration, if required.

Advances blueprint logstash.

Change-Id: I2492b775f6cb096cc2f5838dc1500b99a773f52b

[{'created': '2014-09-30 13:33:37.000000000', 'message': "Call pkill -P properly

We do not want a -<PID>, that's for use with kill, not pkill.

In the process go ahead and announce that we failed to pkill if
in fact we did fail.

This ought to address issues with processes not dying appropriately
in grenade runs when USE_SCREEN=False. The base problem here is
that even when USE_SCREEN=False, processes in icehouse will still be
launched in a screen. Then when ./stop-base is called this pkill
may not match _and_ screen killing portion of screen_stop is not
called because USE_SCREEN=False, despite the fact that screen was in
fact used.

It may be that we'll want to backport the USE_SCREEN/run_process
changes in devstack to icehouse, or just wait until kilo opens.

Change-Id: Id6cbfeec7a871a3c701502c8748f8eb55dcdc3df
"}]
commit_message:
Call pkill -P properly

We do not want a -<PID>, that's for use with kill, not pkill.

In the process go ahead and announce that we failed to pkill if
in fact we did fail.

This ought to address issues with processes not dying appropriately
in grenade runs when USE_SCREEN=False. The base problem here is
that even when USE_SCREEN=False, processes in icehouse will still be
launched in a screen. Then when ./stop-base is called this pkill
may not match _and_ screen killing portion of screen_stop is not
called because USE_SCREEN=False, despite the fact that screen was in
fact used.

It may be that we'll want to backport the USE_SCREEN/run_process
changes in devstack to icehouse, or just wait until kilo opens.

Change-Id: Id6cbfeec7a871a3c701502c8748f8eb55dcdc3df

commit_message:
Don't use DB column names for sort keys

The user shouldn't need to know how data is stored in the database in order
to use the API. Instead, use the same key names as provided in the output
data as possible sort keys.

Change-Id: I02e13e2fb6b1949ef8ee5b9b0b08ed5c8d946c68
Closes-Bug: #1355669

commit_message:
Move begin ping listener to a connect listener

The "reconnect" listener that occurs on transaction begin
is not sufficient for libraries that use engines, connections
and sessions in "autocommit" mode, where no transaction is begun.
So we move our "ping" from the begin phase to the "connect"
phase instead.   We use a newer SQLAlchemy event "engine_connect"
so that we can make use of the Connection and all the disconnect/
invalidation facilities that are included, rather than using
the low-level pool listener which is somewhat legacy.
Since the event was added in SQLAlchemy 0.9.0, a compatibility
layer is added which emulates the mechanics of the
handle_error compatibility layer.

Change-Id: I719fe45e657e747e5f8d64f20059e2b61c79b63d
Closes-bug: #1374497

An attempt to PUT base64-encoded binary data as the 2nd step in storing
a secret resulted in a SQLAlchemy 'already attached' error with the
secret model. This CR adds code to ensure that when repositories
retrieve a model, it is detached. Logic that depended on this attached
behavior was also addressed.

commit_message:
Fix error in two-step secret PUT with base64

An attempt to PUT base64-encoded binary data as the 2nd step in storing
a secret resulted in a SQLAlchemy 'already attached in another session'
error with the secret model. This CR moves to the SQLAlchemy scoped
session which ensures one session per thread. This CR also adds a
simple 'smoke test' script that was used to exercise the API during the
development of this CR, and could be helpful for others looking for a
simple way to test and evaluate their local Barbican API instances.

Closes-Bug: #1374270
Change-Id: Ie50e5f03be7b9b12d82a285a71e2f1b5c2483ea0

commit_message:
Make api_extensions_path a parameter for "neutron"

Currently, the "neutron" class does not support the direct configuration
of the "api_extensions_path" by means of a parameter. However, there is
at least one plugin -- OpenContrail -- which currently requires exactly
this parameter to be set to work. It is hence desireable to be able to
set the parameter directly from within the "neutron" class instead of
having to fiddle with "neutron_config" in local site manifests.

This commit adds the desired functionality and allows the parameter via
"api_extensions_path" to be set directly for the "neutron" class.

Change-Id: I660848100073a3a0067ffb42791bfd80b66c808e

commit_message:
Refactor PXE clean up tests

Make this tests really unit test, leave a separate "full flow"
test for checking the most common case without mocks.
Also add missing test for iscsi_deploy.

Change-Id: Idc85efce2d58e41642a4a72c612df4a5f9f12082
Closes-Bug: #1370487

[{'created': '2014-09-25 07:01:42.000000000', 'message': 'Redact x-subject-token from response headers

When you invoke any OpenStack API of any of the OpenStack services
e.g. glance, neutron, cinder, heat, ceilometer, nova, keystone
then it logs readable x-subject-token at the debug log level in the
respective log files.

Simply redacting the x-subject-token in keystone client response header
before logging it.

SecurityImpact
Closes-Bug: #1371355
Change-Id: Iac16c6358250677544761beea9f5c5d8ba29afac
'}]
commit_message:
Redact x-subject-token from response headers

When you invoke any OpenStack API of any of the OpenStack services
e.g. glance, neutron, cinder, heat, ceilometer, nova, keystone
then it logs readable x-subject-token at the debug log level in the
respective log files.

Simply redacting the x-subject-token in keystone client response header
before logging it.

SecurityImpact
Closes-Bug: #1371355
Change-Id: Iac16c6358250677544761beea9f5c5d8ba29afac

commit_message:
Improve openstacklib::db::mysql test coverage

* Add tests for openstacklib::db::mysql::host_access
* Add tests for other overridable parameters in db::mysql
* Do not test implementation details of host_access from
  within openstacklib::db::mysql tests.

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-09-25 21:25:10.000000000', 'message': "libvirt: Convert cell memory from KiB to MiB before creating xml

Currently, the NUMA topology and placement feature expects that
each cell's memory is specified in MiB. However, qemu expects
cell memory to be specified in KiB. This causes undesired behavior
when using qemu 2.0.0 or lower and outright prevents machines with
NUMA specs from booting when using qemu 2.1.0. This patch simply
converts the value from MiB to the expected KiB before creating
the guest xml. For a more detailed explanation of the consequences
of this bug, please see the bug report.

Change-Id: Ic4518acf6bcee463009437829646de8c83aff6bf
Closes-bug: #1373159
"}, {'created': '2014-09-30 10:42:47.000000000', 'message': 'libvirt: Make sure NUMA cell memory is in Kb in XML

This patch makes libvirt report memory in Mb (as
hardware.VirtNUMATopologyUsage class expects Mb) and that when
generating XML we use Kb as this is what libvirt expects by default.

Change-Id: Ic4518acf6bcee463009437829646de8c83aff6bf
Closes-bug: #1373159
'}]
commit_message:
libvirt: Make sure NUMA cell memory is in Kb in XML

This patch makes libvirt report memory in Mb (as
hardware.VirtNUMATopologyUsage class expects Mb) and that when
generating XML we use Kb as this is what libvirt expects by default.

Change-Id: Ic4518acf6bcee463009437829646de8c83aff6bf
Closes-bug: #1373159

commit_message:
Correct missing vcpupin elements for numa case

We should pin each vcpu into specified numa's cpuset. But the current
code only pin the last vcpu in one cell to specified numa's cpuset.

Change-Id: Ia1cda5e117d7e569e8891bd7c3d03bd6148a0c27
Closes-Bug: #1374902

commit_message:
Remove untranslated PO files

The proposal bot only imports file that are at least 75 % translated.
Remove any PO file that is untranslated or has less than 75 % of
translations.

Checked number of translated entries with:

for i in `find . -name *.po `; do msgfmt --statistics -v $i; done

Whenever a file is again translated sufficiently, the proposal bot will
propose a new patch - thus we do not lose any translations.

Change-Id: I642bd23584e7f29f392fbdc8e1e8bdc6d9a12c9e

commit_message:
Make user creation optional when creating service.

In some cases it is useful to be able to just configure
the service in Keystone and not the service user. This
is the case when e.g. a read only LDAP backend is used.
Added parameters configure_user and configure_user_role
(default to true).

Change-Id: I6b0b7e2554e982550d71d8427ce2ea94f04f55e8
Closes-Bug: 1360232

development.

commit_message:
ignore .idea folder in glance

If we use JetBrains PyCharm as python develop tool, JetBrains PyCharm
would automatically generate its config folder name .idea in the root
dir of your python code.
Many Code projects, such as nova and cinder, have ignore .idea folder.
Project glance should also ignore .idea folder.

Change-Id: I1e3ba1936c8b918aa4669c2d7fceac23a23ca974
Closes-Bug: #1362451

Hi kevin and Andrey,

In nova/network/security_group/security_group_base.py the conditions are given below :

# Verify valid TCP, UDP port ranges
if (ip_protocol.upper() in ['TCP', 'UDP'] and
    (from_port < 1 or to_port > 65535)):
   raise exception.InvalidPortRange(from_port=from_port,
          to_port=to_port, msg="Valid TCP ports should"
            " be between 1-65535")

# Verify ICMP type and code
  if (ip_protocol.upper() == "ICMP" and
  (from_port < -1 or from_port > 255 or
    to_port < -1 or to_port > 255)):
   raise exception.InvalidPortRange(from_port=from_port,
     to_port=to_port, msg="For ICMP, the"
   " type:code must be valid")

According to these condition -1 to 255 port are valid ports.
So these given rules are valid not invalid.

Moreover,issues are solved by this code changes.
Initially 
nova secgroup-delete-group-rule default default icmp 22 22 (valid rule) was throwing AttributeError. 
another side invalid rule for tcp and icmp throwing error as:
nova secgroup-add-group-rule default default icmp -2 -2
ERROR (BadRequest): Invalid port range -2:-2. For ICMP, the type:code must be valid (HTTP 400) 

2.nova secgroup-add-group-rule default default tcp -2 -2 Invalid port range -2:-2. Valid TCP ports should be between 1-65535 (HTTP 400) 


Which means only valid rules are throwing the error(AttibuteError) and invalid rules are not able to add.

For valid rules test cases are passed successfully. Do we need to add test cases for invalid rule..? Because invalid rules are not able to add.'}, {'account_id': 679, 'date': '2014-09-26 17:50:50.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

If you are fixing a bug, you really need to include a test case which would fail due to that bug.  The purpose of tests of this sort is to help highlight accidental regressions, thus the name "regression test".  If there's no way to actually exercise the bug by building a test case, that suggests that it may not actually be a bug.  (Of course, I accept that some bugs cannot easily be exercised with a unit test, but I don't think this one falls into that category.)'}, {'account_id': 12869, 'date': '2014-09-30 12:19:47.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned

Other users not able to see proposed fix.'}]

commit_message:
no way to delete valid and invalid security rule

Previously deleting correct/incorrect security
group rule was throwing the error of
"AttributeError". With this fix, now the valid
and invalid security group rules can be deleted.

Change-Id: Id1ef3ec663e930b726b93803b22c58f7302dcc38
Closes-Bug: #1163469

SSH commands often have to parse an output and do some pattern matchings
(e.g using grep) that makes those commands dependent on the system

commit_message:
Force the SSH commands to use their default language

SSH commands often have to parse an output and do some pattern matchings
(e.g using grep) that makes those commands dependent on the system
language and causing it to fail on systems with a non-english locale
setting.

This patch forces the SSH commands to use their default language
(whatever language the strings in the application was written in) for
output by passing LC_ALL=C as part of the command. For virsh, vmware,
vbox and prlctl the default language is english making the commands from
the SSH driver to work independent of the system language.

Closes-Bug: #1373671
Change-Id: I175d84fca4e10b8c9468bc4fe54ecd865725e39c

commit_message:
Revert "api: add serial console API calls v2"

As described on the bug - the current implementation makes no sense
without an actual client, and depending on the client, the
implementation will need to change, so we don't want this to be a part
of the API since it will not work as is and may need to change.

This reverts commit e89eaf9a7d1f79420648038819ae2481b47fedb3.

Change-Id: Icb1c4ef3bd267267e3fd0bb2d43aa34e2ca79a61
Partial-bug: #1373950

commit_message:
Revert "cmd: add nova-serialproxy service"

As described on the bug - the current implementation makes no sense
without an actual client, and depending on the client, the
implementation will need to change, so we don't want to ship a useless
service.

This reverts commit ea8323eca4f16e4af39d42ac28227aaa5e681d00.

Change-Id: I0db5866d9da688bfa02da850f82e5371c2e3cc3e
Partial-bug: #1373950

commit_message:
Fix DB2 and nosql ceilometer dbsync

* Remove very old and now incorrect check for running
ceilometer-dbsync with nosql.  This is fine to do now, and is
needed when nosql is used for DB2 with ceilometer.

Change-Id: Id31d7dffb3e01513bb0470a7a6f5f07118dc28ef
Closes-Bug: #1373600

commit_message:
Always reset target_power_state in node_power_action

Currently under some conditions target_power_state can be left
on the node, making it impossible to operate on via API.

Change-Id: Iba92c9bfae3616661cadf602618a66d2664264ee
Closes-Bug: #1375641

a few other cmds) to sync up with master; yet on Fedora 20 this

Closes-bug: 1373150
'}]
commit_message:
Fix selinux permissions for non-primary MariaDB/Galera nodes

Galera nodes started after the bootstrap node will use rsync (and
a few other cmds) to sync up with master; yet on Fedora 20 this
is causing a number of selinux AVC denials.

Fedora bug is https://bugzilla.redhat.com/show_bug.cgi?id=1145619

Change-Id: Ifb97b3f92fefdef1d57c87907292aeb4a27c3a49
Closes-bug: 1373150

commit_message:
Functional tests for metadata seeding for glance-manage

Currently there are no functional tests for metadata seeding for
glance-manage. This tests should cover a specific lifecycle of metadata
using three api methods:

db_load_metadefs
db_unload_metadefs
db_export_metadefs

This tests also concerns json files stored in /glance/etc/metadefs.

Change-Id: Icd237252b6374d7457c2636f805a830c241d0a94
Closes-Bug: #1373936

Greatly reduce code duplication in rspec tests of db::mysql

Use shared examples to avoid duplicating tests for both platforms.

Change-Id: I16a77a284070e243c2a46675af419e635a139969

commit_message:
cmd: update the default behavior of serial console

When using serial console we are expecting using a plain websocket
so we should to return the 'ws://' scheme as the default one, also
it makes no sense to handle webserving content since currently
nothing has been implemented in favor of this case.

DocImpact: The 'base_url' option serial_console has been updated
Closes-Bug: #1373950
Change-Id: I0d0e4f7060febec5e0a357cd3e8c05486f2afaa5

commit_message:
Ironic driver must wait for power state changes

The Ironic virt driver was previously returning from power_on,
power_off, and reboot calls immediately after making the request to
Ironic -- but before Ironic had necessarily acted upon it. This could
lead to Nova acting as though the state change was complete before it
actually was.

This patch introduces a new private method which polls Ironic until it
signals that the power state change is complete. With this, the
power_on, power_off, and reboot methods wait for the action to complete
before returning to ComputeManager.

Closes-bug: #1310135

Change-Id: I0bbdd8bc8807a0df43a420825f497842b387c4d5

commit_message:
Fix support for puppetlabs-stdlib<4.2.0

Support for non-array value in the function concat() was added
in puppetlabs-stdlib 4.2.0.

This change adds a fix to support puppetlabs-stdlib<4.2.0
by converting $host to an array.

Change-Id: Ib8e4c7a5f788d1e0bd7440bc93b560df8e39fcf4

commit_message:
Add HashRingManager to wrap hash ring singleton

Currently, the API service creates a new hash ring on every request.
Instead of that, we should cache the hash ring object -- but we should
also expose a way to refresh it when necessary. This method will also
be used by the ConductorManager to cache and refresh the hash ring
when conductors join / leave the cluster.

This patch preserves the existing API behavior by resetting the hash
ring on every request. This should be addressed in a subsequent patch.

Co-Authored-By: Devananda van der Veen <devananda.vdv@gmail.com>

My opinion is that, if we've empirically determined that this is required, then it's what we need to do.

My concern is that we need to make sure people who want to develop on TripleO know what they need to have in order to get a useful test environment. If we can come up with some minimal cloud spec (1seed+3 workload cloud control + 1 workload loud compute nodes perhaps?) that would be good; otherwise perhaps we should simply say that a test environment needs a minimum 24Gb RAM or something like that."}, {'account_id': 8449, 'date': '2014-09-26 06:29:01.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1

trouble is "1seed+3 workload cloud control + 1 workload loud compute " describes (i believe) a 3 node HA setup for the control and a single compute. Fine, but this is *a* setup, I don't think we can really come up with a standard definition here (in order to document it). Getting a 'useful test environment' will mean different things ('just poking', 'want to test this specific thing' etc).

Point I'm trying to make is I can't see how we can document anything beyond the minimum requirements per node, people can work out for themselves based on that.'}, {'account_id': 1926, 'date': '2014-09-26 08:36:46.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Agreed, I know I've pretty much never run locally with more then 1 controller and I usually use 1 compute, maybe we could give an example and say something like individual setups may vary?"}, {'account_id': 9453, 'date': '2014-09-26 08:49:50.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

I completely agree with Marios and Derek's comments.

I would like us to guide a new dev through *a* setup of *a* minimal install, and perhaps give some guidance about the limitations of what they can expect to be able to test in that setup. No setup is going to suit everyone, but at least we can provide a starting point.

But this is all off-topic for this review. We've shown that 3G is what we need for machines that run reliably, so let's get that landed :)"}, {'account_id': 8449, 'date': '2014-09-30 08:36:25.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+2

commit_message:
Bump VM minimum requirments to 3G

Increase the amount of memory required for VMs in a virtual tripleo
environment to 3G. We had been getting a lot of failures in CI on the
ubuntu overcloud jobs, various services were running out of memory.

The CI testenvs have already be rebuilt host 3G VMs.

Change-Id: Ia0fd8e3f86f5ca786356a460c91f33cfaf29c528

commit_message:
Add network-gateway element

Add a new element that allows a gateway device to be set.  Allows
setting a default route other than the one offered by the DHCP lease
from Neutron's DHCP. Useful for when a default route is needed that may
offer access to other networks that may be needed.

Change-Id: I62b874e37070e4ee2e4557fee0bb06faa4264483
Closes-Bug: 1354570

commit_message:
Improve reliability of preseed download in initrd

Occassionally Ubuntu fails to download its
configuration and the installation fails.
This patch enables preseed scripts to attempt
10 times to download the configuration
before failing

blueprint 100-nodes-support

commit_message:
Improve reliability of preseed download in initrd

Occassionally Ubuntu fails to download its
configuration and the installation fails.
This patch enables preseed scripts to attempt
10 times to download the configuration
before failing

blueprint 100-nodes-support

Change-Id: I4dcee04d221c77bbdf82ea280ac836b73654a86e

commit_message:
Stop running check_uptodate in the pep8 testenv

As per this discussion on the mailing list:
  http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2014-September/047160.html

We are going to stop enforcing the correctness of the sample config
file, and move to a separate non-voting check test that notifies us when
it is no longer accurate, thus prompting a human to correct it.

This addresses the issue where config options in dependent libraries
(eg. keystone) repeatedly break our gate, without removing the sample
config file that deployers benefit from.

Change-Id: Ief88a693e4967b32f5f2f71b9a683599527a5129

commit_message:
VMWare: Fix VM leak when deletion of VM during resizing

During the VM resizing, before VM arrive RESIZED state, driver
migrate_disk_and_power_off will initially rename orginal vm
'uuid' to be 'uuid-orig' and clone a new vm with 'uuid' name.
When deletion VM is triggered at this time window, it wouldn't
be able to delete the VM uuid-orig in VCenter and so cause VM leak.
As VM task state will be set to 'deleting' and it can not be used to
determine the resize migrating/migrated state, this fix will
attempt to delete orig VM within destroy phase.

Change-Id: I7598afbf0dc3c527471af34224003d28e64daaff
Closes-Bug: #1359138

Should this lock be per instance? Or is there some reason that the vcenter can't have more than one of these things happening at once?"}, {'account_id': 9172, 'date': '2014-09-25 08:08:10.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

@Michael we need the lock to prevent assigning the same VNC port to several instances. You can see why this is a problem in the bug report which this patch is trying to fix.

Unfortunately, there is no way vCenter to allocate these ports for us simply because VNC is not meant to be the "native" way for accessing VM consoles. The native protocol for accessing VM consoles is VMRC and we will try to leverage this in Kilo.'}, {'account_id': 782, 'date': '2014-09-29 09:35:41.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Code-Review+2

So, its possible that someone else (i.e. not nova) assigns a VNC port while we are inside the lock doing the loop of the VNC port, but thats not really avoidable, I presume.

commit_message:
VMware: prevent race condition with VNC port allocation

When spawning some instances, nova VMware driver could have a race condition
in VNC port allocation. This fix ensures that the lock is done on the
actual setting in the VM configuration spec.

Co-authored-by: Marcio Roberto Starke <marcio.starke@serpro.gov.br>

Change-Id: I70fab021bbf2df418df53e5f47e19cf16dbe45ac
Closes-bug: #1357372

I think that returning the object is definitely the right approach, since we'd have the DB ID and could be sure we're deleting the right thing. However, changing the return value (especially the type of that value) of an RPC call is a bit sticky.

One option would be to just pass a want_object_return=True to the call, which would default to False for preserving old behavior. Thus, if a new client was making the call, we'd return the object, else object.device_name. A comment about how this should be removed for the next major rev should be included so that we're not stuck with that forever.

The alternative would be a new RPC call variant that would return the object, and the compatibility call would just call that one and return $result.device_name. Then, when we rev the API version, it'd be clear that the old interface could just be nuked.

I don't really care which we do, as they're roughly equivalent. We have more examples of the former I think, yet the latter is a little cleaner at api-bump time."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-08-04 15:28:29.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6: Verified-1

commit_message:
Fix creating bdm for failed volume attachment

This commit modifies the reserve_block_device_name method to return the
bdm object, when the corresponding keyword argument is True. This
ensures the correct bdm is destroyed if the attach fails. Currently the
code assumes only one bdm per volume and so retrieving it can cause the
incorrect db entry to be returned.

Change-Id: I22a6db76d2044331d1a846eb4b6d7338c50270e2
Closes-Bug: #1349888

commit_message:
Add HA mode support for Neutron router

HA (high availability) mode support is one of the important topics in
Neutron Juno, and this patch adds HA router mode support to Horizon.

This commit also changes the default value of enable_distributed_router
in the example local_settings.py to False. In Juno release of Neutron,
the distributed router and L3 HA mode cannot be enabled at the same
time and only L3-agent deployment with L3 Router service plugin
support both features. Thus I believe it is reasonable to make both
options default to False to avoid unnecessary confusions to operators.

Closes-Bug: #1370110
Change-Id: I77b0292b761f08b4580846f6d58443f7df9a1f6b

commit_message:
Pop new page when click instance console link

In instance detail page ,when click ' Click here to show only
console',if we want to view other page,we must click browser's
back button to exit the fullscreen mode.But if add '_blank',
then we can view instance console and we can also use the dashboard.

Change-Id: Idbd47138f92f1a9004afde6324e17919d156ac70
Closes-bug:#1290286

commit_message:
Persist usage start and end dates in the session

This patch adds the usage start and end dates to the user's session
so they are saved while navigating between pages.

Closes-Bug: #1373651
Change-Id: I3046b5533eb96f85fb2f90e63b3ff84360ad14c4

commit_message:
Neutron: Using net info from neutron if instance info_cache lost

Unluckly, sometimes instance info_cache will be a emty list, which
cause nova list show instances with no ip. Also these instances
can not be deleted or detached port from.

The patch make it get ports id from neutron througth get ports
API. In this way, we can self-healing even lost network info cahe.

Partial-Bug: #1323475

Change-Id: Ib8e567d300d5825e473dc9f8353a3f585e2b520b

Keystone will automatically create the _member_ role if it does not
exist, so there's no need to do it in os-cloud-config. Further,
explicitly creating it will cause an issue when you go to create the
first user in Keystone.

Keystone will try to add the user to the _member_ role, but use the
default *id*:
http://git.openstack.org/cgit/openstack/keystone/tree/keystone/assignment/core.py#n261

Since os-cloud-config has precreated the role, it has a different id, so
then when Keystone will try and create _member_ again, and failing with
a duplicate entry.

This change was introduced in os-cloud-config via commit:
Ia4d965335f900e03465f45c701f0bd5a3a4a0ea6

Instead of just reverting that commit, I figured we could remove the
_member_ role creation entirely.

We aren't seeing this failure scenario in CI, because we haven't had a
os-cloud-config release in a while apparently and we don't use
os-cloud-config from git (for better or worse).

Change-Id: Iaa05c71173140e68e47357ac8a9ab3fdb276c838

commit_message:
Do not create the _member_ role

Keystone will automatically create the _member_ role if it does not
exist, so there's no need to do it in os-cloud-config. Further,
explicitly creating it will cause an issue when you go to create the
first user in Keystone.

Keystone will try to add the user to the _member_ role, but use the
default *id*:
http://git.openstack.org/cgit/openstack/keystone/tree/keystone/assignment/core.py#n261

Since os-cloud-config has precreated the role, it has a different id, so
then when Keystone will try and create _member_ again, and failing with
a duplicate entry.

This change was introduced in os-cloud-config via commit:
Ia4d965335f900e03465f45c701f0bd5a3a4a0ea6

Instead of just reverting that commit, I figured we could remove the
_member_ role creation entirely.

We aren't seeing this failure scenario in CI, because we haven't had a
os-cloud-config release in a while apparently and we don't use
os-cloud-config from git (for better or worse).

Change-Id: Iaa05c71173140e68e47357ac8a9ab3fdb276c838

commit_message:
Adds tenant_network_conf to tempest.conf

Adds the ability to define tempest.conf's tenant_network CIDR

Needed for large_ops job to achieve connectivity

Change-Id: Iafd8ef88a8c972e720aeafd14e3d1ec6e71cbf86

commit_message:
Add good path test cases of osapi_compute_workers

While fixing issues in Cinder for bug 1367454 I discovered
that Nova doesn't have any good path test cases to make
sure that settings to osapi_compute_workers is being handled
as expected.

This commit adds those test cases.

Change-Id: I161adf9e93bd7ff1389fdbc8f712ae67ed98b613

commit_message:
VMware: Supported images for copy image to volume

VMware VMDK driver supports only images in vmdk disk format
with bare container format for copy image to volume operation.
The vmdk type can be preallocated, sparse, streamOptimized or
thin. This patch adds these details to the config reference.

Change-Id: Id5c6fc5aa70e584982ac7eff79e882134f975822

commit_message:
Added trove replication via cmd line

The trove chapter in the user guide did not have
a section on how to use the cmd line to
set up database instance replication.

This commit covers how to set up replication,
then detach the replica.

Change-Id: Id6191eb6f247d1fd6de0ac8f3ecdd4f7923284c9
Closes-Bug: #1333586

commit_message:
Redefine instance.security_groups as list

This patch is the 2nd time I am patching Horizon to fix a Django
1.7 patch: the rework of the tests seems to have dropped the
fix, so I have to do the work again. Reviewer: please make sure
this doesn't happen again, and that we don't go back to .first().
Please see: https://review.openstack.org/111934/

The two tests modified here were incorrectly defining
instance.security_groups as a single value instead of a list.

Apparently Django 1.7 is no longer happy trying to iterate something that
is not an iterable.

The other test_instance_details_*() were already doing the correct
thing so just copy over the logic.

Change-Id: I92ae19e937e0e3a482fa424585b926e853c4ce8b

[{'created': '2014-09-29 18:04:10.000000000', 'message': 'Fix race condition in ISCSIConnector disconnect_volume

The list of devices returned by driver.get_all_block_devices() will
sometimes contain broken symlinks as the SCSI device has been deleted
but the udev rule for the symlink has not yet completed.

Adding in a check to os.path.exists() will ensure that we will not
consider the broken symlinks as an “in use” device.

Change-Id: Ibb869e10976f894f9e18e9edec6739c2c3bea68c
Closes-Bug: #1375382
'}]
commit_message:
Fix race condition in ISCSIConnector disconnect_volume

The list of devices returned by driver.get_all_block_devices() will
sometimes contain broken symlinks as the SCSI device has been deleted
but the udev rule for the symlink has not yet completed.

Adding in a check to os.path.exists() will ensure that we will not
consider the broken symlinks as an “in use” device.

Change-Id: Ibb869e10976f894f9e18e9edec6739c2c3bea68c

commit_message:
Ability to pass metadata during snapshot create

Metadata as a parameter is supported by the underlying cinder driver.
This is not exposed by the python client. It is helpful to store additional information
for snapshots and can be used for decision within cinder driver during snapshot creation.
Similar functionality exists for volume creation in cinder client and cinder driver.
Updating cli(shell) to accomodate the new metadata parameter
Adding above change for v2

Change-Id: I002221efea1b9994da4a8d200544a88b0ed26277
Closes-Bug: #1341424

[{'created': '2014-09-23 15:07:16.000000000', 'message': "Server SAML metadata publicly

The contents of the SAML metadata is intended to be shared.
Having the SAML metadata being served under the OS-FEDERATION
factory extension would not make it publicly accessible.
This specific route can be moved apart from the rest of federation
code and placed in the pipeline before auth_token to ensure it's
available before the policy engine kicks in.

Change-Id: I361cde0f5d2c8894d6d73bbcdb164bffa9a7f709
"}]
commit_message:
Server SAML metadata publicly

The contents of the SAML metadata is intended to be shared.
Having the SAML metadata being served under the OS-FEDERATION
factory extension would not make it publicly accessible.
This specific route can be moved apart from the rest of federation
code and placed in the pipeline before auth_token to ensure it's
available before the policy engine kicks in.

Change-Id: I361cde0f5d2c8894d6d73bbcdb164bffa9a7f709

[{'created': '2014-09-13 07:56:39.000000000', 'message': "Stop using intersphinx

Remove intersphinx from the docs build as it triggers network calls that
occasionally fail, and we don't really use intersphinx (links other
sphinx documents out on the internet)

This also removes the requirement for internet access during docs build.

This can cause docs jobs to fail if the project errors out on
warnings.

Change-Id: I71e941e2a639641a662a163c682eb86d51de42fb
Related-Bug: #1368910
"}]
commit_message:
Stop using intersphinx

Remove intersphinx from the docs build as it triggers network calls that
occasionally fail, and we don't really use intersphinx (links other
sphinx documents out on the internet)

This also removes the requirement for internet access during docs build.

This can cause docs jobs to fail if the project errors out on
warnings.

Change-Id: I71e941e2a639641a662a163c682eb86d51de42fb
Related-Bug: #1368910

commit_message:
Upload custom configuration for js-draft build.

With CORS support in the API, and custom configuration loading in the
webclient, we can now let our js-draft build connect to a live API and
function like a regular client. This change makes the assumption that
any javascript project will include static docs-draft assets in the
$PROJECT_ROOT/test/draft directory, which will be uploaded as-is to the
same destination as the draft build.

Depends on: https://review.openstack.org/#/c/124201

Change-Id: Ia68f1f5e13098faac9e94c9655cf4bd8aaceb02b

commit_message:
Enhance meter name and threshold validation

Verify that they're not wsme.Unset rather than just coercing to boolean.
This allows to set the threshold to 0.

Fixes bug #1262215

Change-Id: Ied162502fce727f8508a7234e798223808ec6822

commit_message:
Turn off Nova firewall driver when using Neutron

As referenced in the OpenStack documentation, the firewall_driver in
nova.conf should be set to nova.virt.firewall.NoopFirewallDriver, "so
that nova-compute does not perform iptables-based filtering itself".

Without this change, the driver gets set to
nova.virt.libvirt.firewall.IptablesFirewallDriver, which seems to
make networking unusable.

Change-Id: Id9cce0f5f4efe719683aaf3284b128188b61b919
Closes-bug: #1246888

commit_message:
Prevent stable branches to use glancelcient 0.14.0

This version contains a bug introduced that prevents using that specific
version of the client with older openstack deployments. The fix is:
I8c871f11b909337bd7df19b77e606772dbc634b2 and was released in 0.14.1

Change-Id: I46b01da2f2fee805281513434099e4c5ebbee8f9

VMware: validate that VM exists on backend prior to deletion

Attempting to delete an instance that does not exist on the backend
throws an exception (for example UnregisterVM may return this when
running the CI).

Fixes: bug #1300788

(cherry picked from commit 98fb5e56ef96c0c6a8754276e5f8c9c0b7e50fed)

Change-Id: I1b95caec2dad6580db576aa6f80f47913b7c066e

commit_message:
Script to list unreleased changes in all oslo projects

Prints a report showing what has changed in the oslo repositories since
the most recent tag in each. Sample output from today is in
http://paste.openstack.org/show/110788/

Change-Id: I1c7620c66dd9d106384d7513aa053bd233592869

commit_message:
Script to print a list of the official oslo repos

Add a script to print a list of the official oslo repositories. This can
be used as the basis of other tools that do things to those
repositories.

Change-Id: Iee0b73591b0153961606294a44d8db064478f656

commit_message:
libvirt: log exception info when interface detach failed

The detach_interface method is catching a libvirtError and logging an
error message but it doesn't include the contents of the root
libvirtError, so log that information as well for debugging.

Closes-Bug: #1374140

Change-Id: I042c2956c7393a2ee1ccd026421c8df537aa1a87

commit_message:
Clarify virt driver test comments & log statement

The current implementation of nova.tests.virt.test_virt_drivers
indicates NotImplementedError should be caught and logged to
dynamically build the hypervisor support matrix. This is not a
realistic / optimal approach for building the support matrix and
thus this patch updates the code comments accordingly for
clarity. This patch also modifies the logging statement outputted
in such scenarios to better clarify which test case method is
executing.

 Partial-Bug: 1209421

Change-Id: I5d80cdc06207071548fdb5f6852ca96fa8d79776

The reason I set these values to False is so that a user can see the Errors that the datasources have thrown by simply opening up the log.  If verbose/debug are both True, the Errors get buried and are hard to find.  Once these errors are caught and exposed through the API I'm happy to change these back to True.  But for now I think they're better left false.  If they like, developers can set them to True in /etc/congress/config, which doesn't get overridden if you pull a new version of Congress.  But I will change my mind if this hampers someone's workflow."}, {'account_id': 4395, 'date': '2014-09-05 18:36:47.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

I still think the defaults should be true since this is consistent with all the other projects. I understand what you're sayting though. The loggging is very chatty."}, {'account_id': 8215, 'date': '2014-09-08 16:18:03.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

My argument is about usability for the end-user; that trumps an argument for consistency across OS projects.'}, {'account_id': 4395, 'date': '2014-09-09 05:30:57.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

commit_message:
Default setting for verbose/debug should be True

There was a patch that was merged that changed these values to False.
With these values being false it makes it hard for one to track down why
things are failing without enabling it. One can change this setting
to False in their own setup or set: ENABLE_DEBUG_LOG_LEVEL=False in
ones localrc file to turn of debugging.

Change-Id: I816fa767948fd3f7c5f6939625f844fb3a4440a1
Closes-bug: 1364130

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-09-13 07:26:01.000000000', 'message': "Stop using intersphinx

Remove intersphinx from the docs build as it triggers network calls that
occasionally fail, and we don't really use intersphinx (links other
sphinx documents out on the internet)

This also removes the requirement for internet access during docs build.

This can cause docs jobs to fail if the project errors out on
warnings.

Change-Id: I71e941e2a639641a662a163c682eb86d51de42fb
Related-Bug: #1368910
"}]
commit_message:
Stop using intersphinx

Remove intersphinx from the docs build as it triggers network calls that
occasionally fail, and we don't really use intersphinx (links other
sphinx documents out on the internet)

This also removes the requirement for internet access during docs build.

This can cause docs jobs to fail if the project errors out on
warnings.

Change-Id: I71e941e2a639641a662a163c682eb86d51de42fb
Related-Bug: #1368910

commit_message:
Add a section for RPC API impact

Changes to the RPC API should definitely be considered.

This changes the unit test to verify specs for Kilo only
since we shouldn't hold past accepted specs to new template
changes.

Change-Id: I3f8857f92ae80cfef01fb4a88e8bdb6a1add1905

commit_message:
Conductor changes target_power_state before starting work

A race was discovered between when Nova requests a power state change
and when that request is visible in Ironic's API, which could lead to
Nova believing the request was completely satisfied before it
actually started.

A partial fix has been proposed to Nova:
    https://review.openstack.org/124162

This also requires that Ironic change the node's target_power_state from
within ConductorManager *prior* to spawning the background thread which
performs the actual work.

Looking into this exposed another potential race in Ironic whereby
a power state change request could be responded with 202-Accepted,
but the background thread might fail to be started, and no error would
be reported. The new behavior is to set node.last_error in the same
way that this is handled for provision state changes that fail in the
same way.

Change-Id: I4d85c9230bcd9b6e36ffa9a326fda9908fee7e76
Closes-bug: #1310135

commit_message:
Add check for DVR router while creating VPN service

For Juno, VPN services do not work with DVR routers, so any attempt
to create a VPN service when a tenant deploys DVR routers should be
prevented at this point in the release cycle.

This patch also increases test coverage for the unit of code.

DocImpact

Closes-Bug: #1356467

Change-Id: I942fe3ad77439be265db40a58641903b4f441aa5

commit_message:
Use secret parameter for rabbit_password

Rabbit_password configuration was not using secret parameter so it
was visible on the logs.

Change-Id: Idad892f0c461fce53eaa81ec8a7f3cfe871a9d00
Closes-Bug: 1328448
(cherry picked from commit cbac8130da6732a1e8ad1dbcf9aec6ba75b7c20d)

commit_message:
VMware: Remove tests for None in fake._db_content['files']

This looks like a legacy. _db_content['files'] is always initialised,
and checking it for None distracts from what is actually being tested.

This was also the only use of NoFilesFound, so we remove it entirely.

Change-Id: Ided6c71b68a654476512016ddf886e895d75e571

commit_message:
Mandate detach replicas before deleting replica source

If the user attempts to delete an instance which has
replicas attached to it, forbid the delete.

Closes bug: #1362299

Change-Id: I644243aef74d9a34b7726139f9fa5ca8bdb1452c

commit_message:
Pin gem versions for stable branch

This intends to pin all the major gems to the version they were during
development cycle.  This should isolate the existing tests from changes in
rspec, etc.

Change-Id: If7e1b8a7a0f170fe901646f77e9f2f07d0f8ae5b

Since Sahara Dashboard is merged in Horizon in Juno, all references
